        {
          "type": "fast",
          "verdict": "findings_remain",
          "findings": [
            {
              "message": "`path_attr_matches_module_path()` cannot recognize the common `#[path = \".../mod.rs\"] mod foo;` layout: it requires the path component count to exactly equal the logical module path and compares the last component by file stem, so `mod.rs` never matches a one-segment module name. As a result, `is_file_backed_test_module()` will fail open on test-only modules stored as `mod.rs`, and `verify()` will scan and flag valid code in those files.",
              "severity": "P1",
              "file": "libs/infrastructure/src/verify/syn_scan.rs",
              "line": 454,
              "category": "correctness"
            }
          ],
          "hash": "rvw1:sha256:41875d3b51deb1d4a242c2f77024d0ed162db4192128712dfecc634e555c43d4",
          "at": "2026-06-26T12:30:56Z"
        },
        {
          "type": "fast",
          "verdict": "findings_remain",
          "findings": [
            {
              "message": "The new `#[path]` branch fails open: when a `#[path]` attribute is present but does not match the probed file, execution falls back to ident-based matching instead of rejecting the candidate. That means a declaration like `#[cfg(test)] #[path = \"other.rs\"] mod shared_helpers;` can still make `shared_helpers.rs` look test-only and skip real findings. `path_attr_matches_module_path` also drops `.`/`..` components, so traversal-style values can alias the wrong in-root file.",
              "severity": "P1",
              "file": "libs/infrastructure/src/verify/syn_scan.rs",
              "line": 401,
              "category": "trusted-root violation"
            }
